eceased","1298–Female":"1298–Deceased","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","ABT    1300":"about 1300","ABT    1296":"about 1296","1296":"1296","1065":"1065","1382":"1382","1271":"1271","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1269":"1269","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","about 1269":"about 1269","about 1298":"about 1298","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","of,Gwyr cmt,Glamorganshire,Wales":"Gwyr, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Dudleston, Shropshire, England":"Dudleston, Shropshire, England","Kidwelly, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Kidwelly, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Einion","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Einion</i>, <i>ap Eynon</i> ‘son of <i>Einion</i>’. See   Eynon   and compare   Bennion  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."],"variants":[{"name":"Eynon","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>Enniaun</i>, an old Welsh personal name ultimately derived from Late Latin <i>Annianus</i>, but also associated with Welsh <i>einion</i> ‘anvil’, taken as implying stability and fortitude. See also   Beynon   and compare   Onion  ."]}]},{"name":"Dafydd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>David</b> . In widespread use during the Middle Ages, it was later largely replaced by the English form, but since the late 19th century it has come into its own again."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":21,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":46,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":59,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":68,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":113,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Dafydd ap Einion was born about 1269, in Dudleston, Shropshire, England as the son of Einion ap Ednyfed and Gwenllian ferch Rhys. He had at least 4 sons and 1 daughter with Elen Verch Meurig."},"et":{"about 1269–":"umbes 1269–Surnud","1269–Male":"1269–Surnud","1271–Female":"1271–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1065–Male":"1065–Surnud","1296–Male":"1296–Surnud","1298–Female":"1298–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","ABT    1300":"umbes 1300","ABT    1296":"umbes 1296","1296":"1296","1065":"1065","1382":"1382","1271":"1271","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1269":"1269","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","about 1269":"umbes 1269","about 1